        title: "The Philosophy of Utilitarianism", cat: "Psychology", lvl: "Hard", 
        text: "Utilitarianism is an ethical theory that suggests the best action is the one that maximizes 'utility'—usually defined as the greatest happiness for the greatest number of people. Developed by philosophers like Jeremy Bentham and John Stuart Mill, it is a form of consequentialism, meaning the morality of an act is judged solely by its outcome.\n\nThis philosophy provides a mathematical approach to morality. If you have to choose between saving one person or five people, a utilitarian would argue that saving five is the objectively correct choice. However, this leads to difficult ethical dilemmas. For instance, would it be right to harm one innocent person if it saved many others? This is the core of the famous 'Trolley Problem.'\n\nCritics argue that utilitarianism ignores individual rights and justice in favor of the collective good. Despite these criticisms, it remains a highly influential framework in public policy, economics, and healthcare, where leaders must often make difficult decisions about how to distribute limited resources to provide the most benefit to society." 
